  <br/>
  <br/>
  Then, just a couple of months ago, I needed a new laptop. My son returned from the Apple Store with a lovely new MacBook. In the space of a couple of evenings I had the basics of a working website built using the excellent web framework <a href='http://www.rubyonrails.com'>Ruby on Rails</a>.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  I worked hard, although thanks to Ruby on Rails I was able to use agile techniques like <a href='http://www.rubyonrails.org/screencasts'>database migrations</a>, <a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Test_driven_development'>test driven development</a> as well as a splash of <a href='http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AJAX'>AJAX</a> and plenty of other features in a short space of time.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  What you see here is just version one of Music Knows. Our aim is to build a large community of music reviewers which, in turn, will build a long and detailed personal history of some the best, worst and funniest gigs. Please do <a href='/help/contact/'>get in touch</a> if you have any comments or suggestions.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  I'm <a href='http://www.suttree.com/about'>Duncan Gough</a>, and when I'm not posting on here I'm blogging about <a href='http://www.suttree.com'>games and social software</a>, or on <a href='http://www.ecolocal.com'>ecolocal.com</a>, a discussion site for sustainable living and all things green, local and eco-friendly.
